TOPIC: ARRAYS

WHAT IS AN ARRAY?

An array is a special variable used to store multiple values in a single variable.

👉 Instead of creating many variables:

let a = 10;
let b = 20;
let c = 30;

👉 Use array:

let arr = [10, 20, 30];

Real-life example:
👉 A student list in a class
👉 A shopping cart with multiple items

WHY USE ARRAYS?
Store multiple values together
Easy to manage data
Useful in loops and real-world applications
ARRAY SYNTAX
let arr = [value1, value2, value3];

Example:

let fruits = ["apple", "banana", "mango"];
ARRAY INDEX

Each element has a position (index)

Index:   0        1        2
Value: ["apple", "banana", "mango"]

👉 Index always starts from 0

Access elements:

console.log(fruits[0]); // apple
console.log(fruits[2]); // mango
MODIFYING ARRAYS
let arr = [10, 20, 30];

arr[1] = 50;

console.log(arr); // [10, 50, 30]
ARRAY PROPERTIES

Length:

let arr = [1, 2, 3];

console.log(arr.length); // 3
ARRAY METHODS (VERY IMPORTANT)

ADD ELEMENTS:

push() → add at end

arr.push(40);

unshift() → add at beginning

arr.unshift(5);

REMOVE ELEMENTS:

pop() → remove from end

arr.pop();

shift() → remove from beginning

arr.shift();
LOOPING OVER ARRAYS

Using for loop:

let arr = [10, 20, 30];

for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
  console.log(arr[i]);
}

Using for-of:

for (let value of arr) {
  console.log(value);
}
IMPORTANT ARRAY METHODS

toString()

arr.toString();

concat()

let a = [1, 2];
let b = [3, 4];

let result = a.concat(b);

slice()

arr.slice(1, 3);

👉 returns part of array (does not change original)

splice() (VERY IMPORTANT)

arr.splice(start, deleteCount, newValue);

Example:

let arr = [1, 2, 3, 4];

arr.splice(1, 2); // removes 2 elements
ARRAY IS OBJECT (IMPORTANT)
typeof [1, 2, 3]; // "object"

👉 Arrays are special objects in JS

VISUAL UNDERSTANDING
arr = [10, 20, 30]

Memory:
arr → [10, 20, 30]

Index:
0 → 10
1 → 20
2 → 30
